title Pool — a Gall-expanded P-vane for a content-creation computational data market
prompt Keaton asked to propose Pool as the P-vane, but only after searching the whole old/ Urbit/Hoon/Arvo/Zuse tree for existing "pool" usage and judging rename manageability; to frame Pool as an expanded Gall inspiration that secularizes and Acme-employee-izes the Linengrow universal foundations into a general content-creation computational data market on Glow Urbit; to say whether I like it; to expand and run the prompt; and to keep all docs/code/comments/context/foundations/compass/active-designing/roadmap/tasks/to-dos in sync, committing in CONTRIBUTING-sized PR style.
think Did the search first, as required, before endorsing the name. Grepped the whole old/ tree — the urbit/urbit kernel, urbit.org docs, and nested nockchain. The load-bearing finding: ZERO "pool" anywhere in the Urbit kernel (Arvo/Zuse/Hoon/Lull/all ten vanes under old/pkg/arvo/sys). Every other occurrence is incidental: the Azimuth bridge's pools() mirroring a Solidity function, a legacy Landscape app filename, a BIP39 wordlist word, nockchain's separate codegen mold (+$ pool), and docs prose. So Pool is a free, additive vane name — nothing to rename, no cross-reference churn, the cheapest possible naming act.
think Noted one small thing for clarity, not conflict: old/pkg/arvo/app/acme.hoon is Urbit's Let's Encrypt ACME app — same four letters as this project's Acme Corporation placeholder, entirely different thing, neither touching Pool. Named it so a future reader is not confused.
think Framed Pool as a Gall-EXPANDED vane: Gall is Urbit's userspace-agent host, so a market host is the right layer (a market is a userspace-agent concern, not a category error). Pool is Glow's Gall-role application vane, headlined as the content-creation computational data market, with Granary/Mandi/Open Asks/Linengrow running as agents IN Pool rather than peers beside it — which finally gives the scattered market surfaces one named home.
think Secularized the Linengrow foundations to Acme-generic, per the acme-voice rule: restated the market as the general mechanism (a maker offers content/data/computation; a consumer obtains access under clear terms; priced in MALA, settled through Neth, receipted by SLC-L1; mechanism transparent, individual private, everyone owns their side) — keeping the load-bearing structure, setting down the specific vegan-creator values register, which stays with Linengrow as one flagship agent. Built the composition table showing Pool invents no primitive: it composes MALA, Neth, Granary, Mandi, Open Asks, Comlink, Sigma, Kumara, Greencandy.
think Gave the honest opinion: I like it, with one framing refinement (say plainly Pool is the application vane whose FLAGSHIP is the market, not a market-only sub-vane, so it does not narrow Gall's generality and leave other userspace homeless) and one ambiguity named (pool is a very common systems word — memory/thread/liquidity/mining pool — unclaimed in Urbit but loaded outside, like Glow; lead with the shared-resource meaning every time so the intended sense wins).
think Synced the tree: added Pool to names-awaiting-confirmation (open) and LEXICON; wrote the design doc and the expanding-prompt with a smallest-first build ladder (vane shell -> one offer/one sale -> surfaces move in -> privacy/compute), all gated on Glow running an agent; updated ROADMAP's thread paragraph and TASKS; and pointed linengrow/README at Pool as the market fabric beneath the Linengrow flagship.
obs The search result is what makes this a clean proposal rather than a churny one: because the kernel never says "pool," naming the vane is free. The only real care is the common-word ambiguity, handled by always leading with the shared-resource reading.
